There are several issues in this code:

* The reason of the error is that your loop executes `temp=1;` once the deletion has taken place, and this makes the outer loop continue forever, and eventually `curr` will be `null` and `curr.next;` will trigger the exception. 

* You are mixing *instance* and *static* stuff. Although you create an *instance* with `new LinkedList`, you then continue to use static methods and variables... this is wrong. Once you have created `ll`, that `ll` should have instance members that manage the state of *that parcticular* list. So `head` should not be `static`, nor your methods (except `main`), nor the `Node` class, ...

* There is no protection in your code against running outside of the linked list, for instance when the values of `N` or `M` are much larger than the size of your linked list.

* There is no provision in your code to update `head` to `null` in case `M` is zero and `N` is not.

* Not a problem, but it is more common to use camelCase for variables, so name `n` and `m` as lowercase.

Here is a correction of your code:

